    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-12T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-12T17:00:00-05:00" n="782"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d782">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 E.W./7–1244: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-12T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 12, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5472. For Phillips. If proposal outlined in your 5477 July 12 is agreeable to the
                    British, we have no objection to statement being issued by the Supreme Allied
                        Commander.<note n="26" xml:id="d782fn26">For text of the warning, see the
                        London <hi rend="italic">Times</hi>, July 17, 1944, p. 3, col. 3.</note> We
                    would regard such a statement as being without prejudice to the proposal for a
                    further statement on a governmental basis should that be considered
                    desirable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="1256" n="1242" xml:id="pg_1242"/>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For texts of statements by the Secretary of State issued on July 14, 1944,
                        on Nazi atrocities in Hungary and Greece, see Department of State <hi
                            rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 16, 1944, page 59.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
